statement.p:
 Let A =\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 a & b \\
 c & d \\
\end{array}
\right). Derive the formula for A^{-1}.

solution.p:
If we multiply A by an two by two matrix of unknowns, \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 x & y \\
 z & w \\
\end{array}
\right) , and equate that product with the identity matrix, we get
	\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 a x+b z & a y+b w \\
 c x+d z & c y+d w 
\end{array}
\right)=\left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 1 & 0 \\
 0 & 1 \\
\end{array}
\right)

If we assume that both a and c are both nozero and we multiply the two equation on the left by c and a, respectively we get \begin{split}
	a c x+b c z= c\\
	a c x+a d z= 0 \\
	\end{split}
	We can then subtract the second equation from the first, eliminating x to get (b c - a d)z = c \Rightarrow z=\frac{-c}{ad-bc}
	We can then substitute this value of z into c x+d z= 0 to get x=\frac{d}{ad-bc}. Notice that the algebra makes sense as long as \det{A}=ad -bc \neq 0. Also a and c can't both be zero.  If either is zero we can derive the same final result. The other set of equations for the second columns are solved in a similar way.

statement.p:
 Prove by induction that for n \geq 1, \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 a & 0 \\
 0 & b \\
\end{array}
\right)^n= \left(
\begin{array}{cc}
 a^n & 0 \\
 0 & b^n \\
\end{array}
\right).

p.me:
     \begin{split}
		\left(
		\begin{array}{cc}
		 a &0 \\
		 0 &b \\
		\end{array}
		\right)^{n+1}
				&=\left(
					\begin{array}{cc}
					 a &0 \\
				 	0 &b \\
					\end{array}
					\right)^n 
					\left(
						\begin{array}{cc}
						 a &0 \\
						 0 &b \\
						\end{array}
							\right) \\
	   &=\left(
				\begin{array}{cc}
				 a^n &0 \\
				 0 &b^n \\
				\end{array}
				\right)
					\left(
					\begin{array}{cc}
					 a &0 \\
					 0 &b \\
					\end{array}
					\right) \quad \textrm{by the induction hypothesis.}\\
			&=
						\left(
					\begin{array}{cc}
					 a^{n+1} &0 \\
					 0 &b^{n+1} \\
					\end{array}
					\right) \quad \blacksquare
	\end{split}

\begin{split}
 \det  A^{n+1} & =\det \left(A^nA\right)\quad \textrm{ by the definition of exponents}\\
   &=\det \left(A^n\right)\det (A)\quad \textrm{ by exercise 5} \\
   &=(det  A)^n(\det  A)\quad \textrm{ by the induction hypothesis }\\
  &=(\det  A)^{n+1}
\end{split}

